                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-346-off1782 t18280911-346-victim1874"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            . I am a <rs id="t18280911-346-viclabel1783" type="occupation">baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-346-victim1874 t18280911-346-viclabel1783"></join>, and live in New-street, Covent-garden. The prisoner was in my employ on the 13th of June; he was to receive money for me, and account to me every night.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-346-person1875">
                  SARAH 
                  KENT
               <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1875" type="surname" value="KENT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1875" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1875" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with 
               <persName id="t18280911-346-person1876">
                  Samuel 
                  Kent
               <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1876" type="surname" value="Kent"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1876" type="given" value="Samuel"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1876" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , a publican. I paid the prisoner several sums of money for his master- I paid him 3s. 4d. but I do not know the day.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-346-person1877">
                  MARY 
                  ANN KENT
               <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1877" type="surname" value="ANN KENT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1877" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1877" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took in some bread of the prisoner, and paid for it - we began to pay on the 7th of June - bread was brought every day by the prisoner - we paid for it as we had it; it was from the 7th to the 14th of June - I cannot tell any sum; I paid him, but I paid him some shillings.</p>
               <p>JOHN MANNING re-examined. Q. During that week were you at home? A. Yes, the prisoner came and accounted for monies he had received, but he brought none from Kent's; he said he had not received it, and it was booked.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did I bring you any money? A. Yes, and said it was from several customers; but never during that week did I take so much of him as was received from the Kent's.</p>
               <p>Q. Was it not customary for those employed by you to keep back part of the money they received as part of their wages? A. No, it was not customary, but you said sometimes that you wanted 1s. or 2s., and I put it down when you told me of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-346-person1878">
                  JAMES 
                  ASHLY
               <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1878" type="surname" value="ASHLY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1878" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-person1878" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took up the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was advised when I was acquitted here last Sessions to go to my prosecutor for my wages, and then he made this charge against me.</p>
               <p>PROSECUTOR. He was acquitted then, but not on this charge - I did not owe him any wages; he said he came for some things which he left in the bakehouse.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. But did he come for wages? A. I did not conceive I owed him any; I had paid him some money due, but I did not know of his having received this money at that time, till I took the bill to Kent's on the 14th of June.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was remanded to Tothill-fields to see if there was any other charge against me.</p>
               <p>PROSECUTOR. No, he was remanded to bring up other witnesses - it was on a charge of theft - for taking bread and selling it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-346-verdict1784" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-346-verdict1784" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 24.</p>
